      {
        "user": "How does \"gradient descent\" differ from stochastic gradient descent (SGD)?",
        "assistant": "Gradient descent and stochastic gradient descent differ mainly in **how they compute the gradient at each update step**.\n\n### Gradient descent\n\nIn standard, or **batch gradient descent**, the algorithm computes the gradient using the **entire training dataset** before updating the parameters.\n\n\\[\n\\theta = \\theta - \\alpha \\nabla J(\\theta)\n\\]\n\nBecause it uses all data at each step, the update direction is more accurate but can be slow for large datasets.\n\n### Stochastic gradient descent, SGD\n\nSGD computes the gradient using **one randomly selected training example** at a time.\n\n\\[\n\\theta = \\theta - \\alpha \\nabla J_i(\\theta)\n\\]\n\nwhere \\(J_i(\\theta)\\) is the loss for a single training example.\n\nBecause it updates after each example, SGD is usually much faster per update, but the updates are noisier and less stable.\n\n### Key differences\n\n| Feature | Gradient descent | Stochastic gradient descent |\n|---|---|---|\n| Data used per update | Entire dataset | One example |\n| Update frequency | Less frequent | Very frequent |\n| Gradient accuracy | More accurate | Noisy estimate |\n| Speed per update | Slower | Faster |\n| Convergence path | Smooth | Noisy/zig-zag |\n| Large datasets | Can be expensive | More scalable |\n\nIn practice, many machine learning systems use **mini-batch gradient descent**, which is between the two: it uses a small batch of examples per update instead of the whole dataset or just one example.",
