        "user": "How does \"gradient descent\" differ from Newton's method?",
        "assistant": "Gradient descent and Newton’s method are both iterative optimization methods, but they differ in what information they use and how they choose each step.\n\n### Gradient descent\n\nGradient descent is a **first-order** method. It uses only the **gradient**, which tells the direction of steepest increase of the function.\n\nTo minimize a function, it moves in the negative gradient direction:\n\n\\[\n\\theta_{t+1} = \\theta_t - \\alpha \\nabla J(\\theta_t)\n\\]\n\nwhere \\(\\alpha\\) is the learning rate.\n\nSo gradient descent asks:\n\n> “Which direction goes downhill, and how big a step should I take?”\n\nThe step size must be chosen manually or adjusted using a learning-rate schedule.\n\n---\n\n### Newton’s method\n\nNewton’s method is a **second-order** method. It uses both the **gradient** and the **Hessian matrix**, which contains second derivatives and describes the curvature of the function.\n\nThe update is:\n\n\\[\n\\theta_{t+1} = \\theta_t - H^{-1} \\nabla J(\\theta_t)\n\\]\n\nwhere \\(H\\) is the Hessian matrix of second derivatives.\n\nNewton’s method asks:\n\n> “Given the local slope and curvature, where is the minimum likely to be?”\n\nBecause it uses curvature information, it can often take more direct steps toward the minimum.\n\n---\n\n### Key differences\n\n| Feature | Gradient descent | Newton’s method |\n|---|---|---|\n| Type | First-order method | Second-order method |\n| Uses gradient? | Yes | Yes |\n| Uses Hessian/curvature? | No | Yes |\n| Step size | Controlled by learning rate | Determined using curvature |\n| Cost per step | Usually cheaper | Usually more expensive |\n| Convergence | Can be slower | Often faster near the minimum |\n| Scalability | Better for large models | Harder for very high-dimensional models |\n\n### In machine learning\n\nGradient descent and its variants, especially mini-batch SGD, are widely used in deep learning because they scale well to huge datasets and models.\n\nNewton’s method can converge very quickly for smaller problems, but computing and inverting the Hessian is often too expensive for large neural networks.",
